USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It even becomes comic, the assiduous effort with which Barack Obama, president with the reputation of wise, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan question, which he himself considered very simple.
When he ended up letting his long-awaited doctrine sweat through, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper since Bush’s Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text even several times the expression "as in Iraq", he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of Bush's speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into an Iraq consumed by civil war as being “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to be so successful that the newspapers at present do not speak at all of Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, however, objectively speaking, he left his successor with a much more favourable final situation than could have been expected.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was once again the campaign commanders who asked him to increase the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House’s reluctance despite the habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he at least defrauded the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to pull out the promise of 5,000 more from Europe, even though he originally counted 10,000.
What is causing the most problems in Obama's entire strategy appears to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and complete the whole process within three years.
Many doubt that an increase of half will bring the same fruits as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out by the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders on a day-to-day basis according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain nothing but dust in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is singularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity as to the relationship, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "prompt-to-act state", which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is perplexed by his voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and it is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a heart that is purely romantic and out of reality can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "prompt return home" will bring a real miracle.
From a political point of view, defining a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it as the indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is turning negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the enhanced sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only rustine for Obama is the fact that he has three years until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
