Pneumococcal vaccination will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococcal disease will reverse old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
There are already voices that say mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The pharmaceutical institute already defines the maximum prices that health insurance will pay for vaccines.
Specialists also see clearly in the vaccination process.
Another vaccination.
Free vaccines for August children.
Since January, children born last year from August 2 can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococcal diseases.
The condition is that they have not been vaccinated yet.
If you started the vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of vaccine should be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcal disease.
Yet parents paid 1600 kroner or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Experts estimate that every year health insurance companies spend 300 to 450,000 kroner in vaccine doses.
They do, however, save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 crowns a year on all vaccinations for children.
The reimbursed vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococcus is the cause of inflammations of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammations of the meninges and blood poisonings.
According to hospital investigations, there are up to 28 deaths of children under 10 years of age caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced the reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions regarding a possible obligation to vaccinate in the future.
From January, it must be paid by insurance and optional.
For example, Nahlas Rudolf Kalovsko, president of the association, said that mandatory vaccination would be more positive.
Its association has long promoted vaccination against pneumococcal diseases.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy that we were able to impose at least this.
I think this is a direction that must now be followed,” Kalovsko said.
But the health ministry does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination process.
We are not considering it at all at the moment, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sr.
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochov, president of the Specialized Society of Pediatricians, acknowledges that a voluntary vaccination will have its flaws.
If all children were vaccinated, we could consider a reduction in the renewals of vaccinations "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum I understand the decision making the vaccination optional," says however Cabrnochova.
Experts predict that as early as next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will vaccinate their infants.
Vaccination against pneumococcal disease also marks a break in the fact that it is the first vaccination of children that is financed by insurance and not the State.
Cabrnochov explains that insurance should free up funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their own products.
This is, however, related to the concerns of pediatric practitioners, which concern the purchase of vaccines.
The original intention was to have the vaccines purchased by insurance, with doctors receiving them in the same way as other vaccine products provided by the state.
Some MPs feared, however, that this would allow insurance companies to "deduct the sums of health insurance".
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance to reimburse them.
It is estimated that individual pediatricians will have to invest nearly 40,000 kroner per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochova.
