The United Nations group has draft plans for reducing emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- returned to the limelight on Friday, due to the release of a paper highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations backing most of the load, in the coming times.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it illuminated the path to take.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in negotiations that are running out of time, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Drafted by a UN special working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, in the current and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could decrease their carbon production and what the upper limit of global temperature rise would be that officials would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN Executive Secretary-General on Climate Change Yvo de Boer described as the “complete picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also restarted negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, the U.S. climate negotiator, rejected any discussion that would require industrialized countries to reduce greenhouse gases, in comparison to the voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies if they were not funded by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is getting tougher on China than the Bush administration did two years ago.
The United States is not going to sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, Stern said, also regretting that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the U.S. top negotiator either lacked “common sense” or was “extremely irresponsible” for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not help China financially to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the world’s major powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than rescuing the planet, with China and the U.S. wrangling over their respective obligations as poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives of acting more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said it was not surprising that major powers were fighting over who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold large emitters accountable for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also a Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries that are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say the negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission’s climate unit, said the action of small island states has “put political pressure on the entire political process,” in part by what they are now unified and asking emerging economies such as China and India, to act.
Debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most of the outstanding issues before heads of government came to an agreement.
High-level officials such as India's Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China's Deputy Minister flew down from their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and news conferences, so they could make claims that would be studied over the next week.
The real picture of the rally -- in which 13,000 people walk in and out of the convention center every day -- of activist guitar players performing nightly shows mocking countries that they think are betraying themselves and that proposals are being written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the big leagues,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
