While the court was to consider the admissibility of the action initiated by Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers, the pleadings of the lawyers sometimes turned to large family unpacking Friday.
For example, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer mentioned three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was wary of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
Françoise, I have never been able to talk to her since her marriage.”
For its part, the Nanterre public prosecutor's office again found that the complainant was not admissible to act, especially since a guardianship judge refused in recent days to grant her request to open judicial protection proceedings for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to take legal action, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in her place," said prosecutor Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court finally decided that it would rule once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms Bettencourt-Meyers.
The managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it used to be, to impose on consumers products thought by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors returns regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emergent part of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilisation seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, in particular R&D and, even more, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI “requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision”; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that the recipes of authoritarian management totally oppose.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I could see that, faced with a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many detours, to do priority... which it has always done.
Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the great engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behavioral theory, reactivated recently by the American "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens the leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for the world today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to achieve a part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies resulting from the Functional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "in place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of a robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo speech: 'Just War' is worth praise to right to Obama
The American right on Friday welcomed the speech delivered the day before in Oslo by Barack Obama, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who had mocked the award to Mr. Obama on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Ms. Palin, the Republican Party’s right wing muse, told USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the topic of war “sometimes necessary” in her newly published memoirs.
War is, of course, the last thing the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We need to stop these terrorists there, she said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 additional troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a “very good job” in Oslo.
I thought the speech was really good, said the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential speech.
In some ways, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed during the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected official, considered by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a leftist president" remind the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not give a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, former pen of George W. Bush reconverted columnist at the Washington Post, Mr. Obama delivered "a very American speech".
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it", said Mr. Gerson.
Among the few on the right not to be convinced, a Bush-era hawk, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton, called the speech “dull, charred, and uninspired” on the National Review Online website.
To the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When you wrap the war in the notion of justice, you can easily justify the massacre of innocent people, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained glowing with praise for the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel was awarded prematurely to Mr. Obama, called his speech a "superproduction" even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression," the daily said.
Obama “made the right speech,” the New York Times said, calling him “both dark and uplifting.”
Roads: three marathons for a deal that saves Christmas supplies
After three sessions of negotiations-marathon, the unions of the road sector and TLF, the only employers' organization to have remained until the end, have reached Friday evening an agreement that ends the slogan of strike and the threat to the supplies of Christmas.
During the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "rejoiced" by this agreement, after several sessions of negotiations, started Wednesday morning.
After a second night of talks, the negotiators had parted ways in the early morning on Friday, with the hope of quickly signing the agreement text in the late morning.
And this even if three employers’ organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OUR) had slammed the door.
But it took still more than six hours of a meeting started at 11am for everyone to agree and for the text to be signed at 6pm.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to businesses" and "it was to be feared that it would disrupt the holiday season," Bussereau said.
The text foresees an increase in wages of 4% for the lowest salaries (in local and regional road transport), and 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
In hourly rate, for low-wage earners, "we go from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It's not much, but we start from a very far, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Either we will give orders to our militants that there are no blockades, no blockades of supply centers.
But we can always have a few recalcitrants who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, praised "a good deal", even though it was "difficult to concede the increases on high wages given the international competition".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros monthly for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
This is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) called it an "acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for an increase in travel costs of 3%, and the holding of general statements of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will notably address the issue of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr. Bussereau recalled that "a decrease of 100 million euros of employer charges" was the subject of a government amendment to the bill of amending finance for 2009, voted on the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote it "in identical terms".
The signature of TLF allows the agreement to apply first to companies that are members of this organization, and second, to the entire profession, in case of extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be done "as soon as possible", assured Mr. Bussereau.
Opposition from employers' organizations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "market of dupes", because the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to compensate part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate urgently, not as a conclusion of a shared analysis, but so as not to upset the turkey eaters of the next New Year's Eve, lamented Unostra.
For the Otre, the agreement risks "digging the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
RER A: disruptions this weekend, unions unhappy with RATP proposals
Disruptions on the RER A, France’s largest urban transit line, will continue over the weekend, as a meeting Friday on the 2nd day of strike between unions and RATP management left them hungry for their premium demand.
Saturday and Sunday, for this important shopping weekend before Christmas, there will be trains between 10:00 and 20:00, at the rate of one train out of two on the central section (between La Défense and Nation) and one train out of four outside the central section.
Interconnection with SNCF will be suspended at Nanterre Prefecture, forcing passengers to change trains.
Galeries Lafayette, which expects 200,000 customers every day, was delighted that "the RATP is making efforts to serve department stores".
The RER A crosses from west to east the Paris conurbation.
The RATP section runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
On Friday, about one in two trains operated during rush hour, and almost no trains in off-peak hours, as expected.
Like Thursday, there was no rush on the docks, the Ile-de-France had organized.
Thus in the early morning, the station of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) was much less frequented than usual, especially because of the absence of middle and high school students.
In Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne), Jack Nbakina, a 29-year-old engineer, explained that he had risen “an hour and a half earlier, to be sure to arrive on time”.
The Saint-Lazare station did not experience saturation, said the SNCF, which had planned a supervision of agents and law enforcement.
The RER A operated by the SNCF from or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or left Saint-Lazare station to reach the metros.
New general assemblies of strikers will be held on Saturday and Sunday, which will examine the results, deemed "lean" by the unions, of a meeting with the management on Friday afternoon.
The RER Director proposes to negotiate a specific protocol for the RER A on all aspects, working time, career development etc.
This is not what drivers want, who demand a premium due, according to Thierry Garon (South).
The RATP even puts its premium proposals in parentheses, was indignant the CGT, stressing that the management "was not screwed to solve a problem while at the drivers and the SNCF it is done".
A new meeting is scheduled on Monday for "a broader review of the conditions of practice of the profession," said the RATP.
The unions were also told that the company was "laughing at weekend users".
In the morning, some 150 drivers had invaded an establishment committee at the headquarters in Paris.
It was then that the management, which until then refused any discussion during the strike, had suggested "in a concern of appeasement" the meeting.
The conflict threatens to widen to RER B on Tuesday, after the filing of a notice by Unsa and Independents.
The unions demand a premium of 120 euros (Unsa) to 150 euros including 30 euros variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, South, Independent) and complain of the deterioration of working conditions on this line to the million daily travelers.
The drivers of RER, all in the second part of their career, receive from 2,200 to 2,700 euros gross as well as 600 to 650 euros in premiums, for staggered hours, Sundays and public holidays.
Turkish Justice Dissolves Pro-Kurdish Party, Ruling With Consequences
Turkey’s Constitutional Court on Friday ruled on the dissolution of the country’s main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by angry protests in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision is likely to greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a “home of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity,” Court President Hasim Kiliç told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, said Kiliç, adding that 37 of the party's cadres, including its president Ahmet Turk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Turk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as unlabelled parliamentarians.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, said it had "no organic ties" to the PKK but refused to call it a terrorist organization and called on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government has reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights, in an attempt to dry up Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders had said a breakup could lead to heightened tensions in southeastern Anatolian, where numerous protests against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan have escalated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
Upon the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the large city in the south-east populated mainly by Kurds.
Law enforcement fired tear gas canisters and used water cannons, as protesters threw molotov cocktails or stones, with slingshots.
A hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Tork claimed that the decision of the Justice will "deepen despair".
Turkey cannot solve this issue by banning a party, he told reporters.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve anything, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a total torpedo of the democratic opening launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow can fall
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a very harsh winter.
But the head of the road clearing and sandblasting service (FES) makes it clear that this is not to annoy citizens.
It is simply so that the agents can test the technique of the vehicles and learn to master them well.
And according to the meteorologists, it could well be for this weekend.
More than 300 agents and 120 vehicles stand ready to tackle snow and ice.
The FES follows a very elaborate plan here.
Mr. Brauburger explains that as soon as it starts to snow on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles run along 20 main routes (referred to as A routes).
This includes high-traffic streets, main thoroughfares, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstrasse.
Also included are fire brigade access, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as the Atzelbergstrasse.
The FES agents begin their service at three o'clock in the morning.
In case of need, the 1040 kilometers of road must be salted with a road melt that adheres well, in 3 hours of time maximum.
This is why the FES service starts at 3am "so that the roads are clear when the daily migration traffic begins".
Where it gets harder is when the snow starts to fall at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the service of clearing and sandblasting of the roads "because no motorist is willing to let through the salting vehicles".
Then, if it does not snow anymore, we take care of access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Strasse.
Side lanes and side streets come last.
Mr. Brauburger knows that there are always a few complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the FES pedestrian team set off to clear priority areas deemed dangerous and passages.
As for bike paths, the FES services generally cannot take care of them.
Brauburger said there is a special service in Frankfurt to monitor the condition of the bridges between 10 p.m. and 4:30 a.m.
As ice forms very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
Sometimes the police also call on this special service in case of need.
The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long and 1.50 meters high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended in sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues reported in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was at the time part of the land of the supercontinent, Pangaea and was towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the relationships, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a Triassic sedimentary layer.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have uncovered the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories concerning the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indians' word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a very exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it allows to confirm certain theories concerning the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, when the saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor which later appeared and from which descend the birds, sauropods, long-necked quadrupeds, and those related to them and the ornithischian herbivores of which the species such as the ornithischian are part.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found evidence that the Tawa hallae had small air sacs in its bones at the level of the skull, just like birds that are descendants of theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
As the related line of the immense sauropods also possessed air sacs and a light bone, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, the researchers concluded that saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three great evolutionary lineages divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. all the landforms that formed the supercontinent Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that may have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the silesaur, that lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a dinosaur-like group.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are in South America a large number of dinosaur fossils that have been preserved while practically none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of current crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread all over the planet, thus promoting the development of many new species, while others, related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate the competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favorite meteorite blossomed from a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that since that time vegetated in the shadows: they were mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley in California.
There are those of lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec City, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
The police evacuation of the casino from J.W. Goethe University in Frankfurt is making waves all over the world.
278 professors and lecturers from J.W. Goethe University and other higher education institutions in Germany, Europe and North and South America express their solidarity with the protesting students of the Westend Campus.
In a statement written in German and English, they condemned the police intervention demanded by the university's steering committee.
Last week, the president of the Werner Mueller-Estler University evacuated buildings occupied by striking students and teachers after walls and artwork were smeared with graffiti.
Five students were injured during the evacuation.
The signatories believe that the degradations did not justify "such a violent intervention by the police commando against the students and teachers who had organized their own courses".
Evacuation represents an "unacceptable interference" with freedom of research and education.
Focusing attention exclusively on acts of vandalism serves only to “delegitimize and criminalize the protest” and attempts to forget the reasons for the mobilization.
The Steering Committee of the University has thus avoided the debates that would be essential.
The court officials demand that the criminal proceedings initiated be immediately suspended.
The majority of the occupants did not take part in the damage.
Legitimization of protests
Young people from the Verdi service union and the German Trade Union Confederation (DGB) show solidarity with the students.
The protests are just a legitimate expression of growing concern for our own future, says Alexander Klein, Verdi’s regional youth secretary.
As for the Minister of Science of the Land of Hesse Eva Kuehne-Hurmann (CDU), she took up the cause for the action initiated by the President of the University and the police.
We thank the President of the University.
Any occupation and degradation of the premises is totally unacceptable, she told the regional parliament of Wiesbaden last Thursday during the television show Aktuelle Stunde.
We understand the meaning of the protests but do not accept vandalism, said CDU Member of the Regional Parliament Peter Beuth.
The parliamentary groups of the SPD, the Greens and the Left (die Linke) did not share this view.
The CSU is taking the pretext of a few painted walls to criminalize the protests, said Janine Wissler of the Left Party (Linke)
Instead of thinking about the students’ arguments and demands, we evacuate them.
The Left Party has tabled a motion that requires the Minister of the Interior to submit a report on the conditions of police intervention.
The new “Silicon Valley”
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place of search for secret weaponry, under strict surveillance.
Today with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the town has a reputation as the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
Important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics are located there.
As early as September 2008, representatives from Zelenograd established links with Riedberg, the place of science in Frankfurt – with the university institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives from Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a “Protocol of Close Collaboration”.
The signatories were Moscow Vice-Mayor Juri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz Head of Project Section for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of the FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will allow FIZ companies to enter the rapidly expanding Russian market.
On the other hand, Russian scientific societies want to obtain contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is home to famous Soviet research institutes and companies.
It includes the Moscow Institute of Electrical Engineering, the major firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The municipality was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for weapons research.
Zelenograd (literal translation “Green City”) takes its name from the wooded hills at the heart of which the research centers are located.
The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be placed high enough.
For its supporters it is nothing less than the “new heart of Europe”.
S21 is much more than the burying of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Wuerttemberg, into a desperate chaos of construction sites for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 80s.
Head-end stations, with tracks that ended in the middle of the city, had the reputation at the time of being the relics of 19th century transport technology that acted as the brake shoe of modern rail traffic because it once took a long time to get locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – this is what needs to be done.
This is why the train stations at the head of the line have to disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart too: a train station, which is about halfway on the Trans-European Railway Magistrale between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava, hence the slogan "the heart of Europe".
The realization of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 80s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners recognized that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, the stations at the head end of the line no longer pose any real problems of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with railcars and pilot car at both ends.
However, the construction of Stuttgart 21 is now underway next to the new route of the inter-city line to Ulm.
Regional and municipal policies prevailed.
The railway company is on the side because it is the taxpayer who bears the risks of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public company.
From an urban point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
One obtains an urban space that – if one believes the graphs of computer generated planners – will be very green.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
The station of passage and the enlargement of the section are designed for a traffic of persons to which was attributed - and it is typical of the 80s - a huge growth.
At the time, there was no competition for cheap flights.
Modern traffic policy should first focus on strengthening freight traffic as rail transport is much more environmentally friendly than trucking on the road.
But the new layout, with its inclinations, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious indirectly concerns many other railway projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the Swabian project.
That's the official number.
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion are more realistic.
One thing is for sure, in the next decade this money will be missing for other junctions and bottlenecks in the network.
The list of the Ministry of Transport mentions a total of sixty major projects.
One of the most important is the widening of the section through the Rhine valley by 180 good kilometers.
Since 1987 this line has been built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent to press the mushroom here thoroughly.
But the S21 project has the effect of a brake shoe.
The Rhine Valley route is on its way to becoming the bottleneck for international freight traffic right in the heart of Europe.
Government reviews decision on airport
In the Regional Parliament of Wiesbaden, the Land Government raised the possibility of appealing to the judgment of the Administrative Court of Hesse concerning the prohibition of night flights.
Minister of the Economy Dieter Posch (FDP) announced that the CDU/FDP coalition had appointed experts to review the Administrative Tribunal’s ruling from a legal perspective, which is a document with more than 400 pages.
The Kassel court had justified in a written document that the Land should adapt the regulations concerning the prohibition of night flights in the event that the project of construction of the north-west landing strip of Frankfurt airport would be carried out.
The authorisation to land 17 aircraft between 11 p.m. and 5 a.m., as envisaged by the Land Government, is not compatible with the legal protection of citizens against nocturnal air pollution.
