The worlds of dreams
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in psychic patients, or under the effect of drugs, that the limits between imagination and reality are confused.
As long as these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our darkened rooms, we can indulge unhindered in the wildest dreams and fantasies.
However, he who, when awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, soon has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in psychic patients or under the effect of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but which sometimes pushes the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases it is called visions, in the worst of madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect stand out, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of neurotransmitting substances in the brain - primarily dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and achetylcholine - breaks down and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often occur during schizophrenic psychosis.
The earth's force of attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always focused on the relationship between madness and dreams.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of waking-dream; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
It's autumn 2001 when Henning T turns into a comic book character.
His body is in two dimensions with garish colors.
Earth's attraction no longer has any power over him, he's hovering above the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him are winged, grimacing devil creatures, bleeding mouths, showing teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over the body.
Loud, nasty, screaming voices coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. pulls two cables out of his stereo, loops it and attaches it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and passes the loop around the neck.
He jumps.
