Let it serve as a lesson for you, shout the voices in a choir to snatch his eardrum. "Go to a clinic and get treated!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last one is 2 years old, the first one is almost 20 years old.
It was triggered by LSD.
Diagnosis: schizoaffective psychosis, paranoid, in addition it is manic-depressive, it takes drugs for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness and has been married for three years.
During psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despairs.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers at least once in their lifetime from schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenia crisis, the people concerned can no longer tell the difference between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper-excitement, which can cause them to suffer hallucinations, megalomania, relationship madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment, or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned under the sensations.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the Department of Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitetsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is right in the middle of the situation, all with a meaning centered on him.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they do not have the ability to adjust reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experiencing a hallucination once in a lifetime.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, “the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis, is basically preserved.”
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the lived takes place in a real setting.
Why our brains make this kind of cabrioles, is always an enigma for researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause everyone to momentarily lose the perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
The researchers assume that the people involved have very small brain damage.
It is assumed that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But what is still unexplained is the way in which the abnormality of the neural system occurs and furthermore the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if there is predisposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brain heats up.
What’s crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Luebeck, is that psychotics suffer from hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy expensive drugs to get them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of perspective.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena for ten years: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also of an impressive number of other pathologies.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma.
It is surprising to find that under certain conditions even the brains of healthy people are prone to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions are overactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain heats up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this state just like a brain injury or psychosis.
But also lack of stimulus, stress, heartbreak or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one-third of participants admitted to experiencing a hallucination at least once in their lifetime.
