Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She got her baccalaureate last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago the hallucinations stopped.
Since she came into contact with psychologist Kasten via the internet, she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or doesn’t have enough stimulation, the likelihood is high that they will have hallucinations after a while.
I guess the brain isn't busy enough, so there's animation.
Sarah K., the only daughter, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13, that the man she called Dad, since she was old enough to think, was not her real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, so it’s very difficult for people like Sarah K to tell the difference between illusion and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychoses.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
This is why Kasten advises her patients to cherish hallucinations as a special talent.
There is only one step between the dream and the hallucination.
In our world too focused on consciousness, we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician of the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Dusseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious illness, painful but also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid form of experience, a particular form of dream-induced consciousness modification.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is awake.
The oneroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully aware, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that harms his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dream and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation that is in itself intolerable, an organizational capacity that is given to us, men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich-based art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Change of Heart" as an action to save the soul.
He is 49 years old, when his conscious mind goes on a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; meanwhile, his body is condemned to remain motionless in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created from scratch, visits foreign places, travels back in time. He sees himself as an old man in bed in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lived in the Middle Ages among nobles who made blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He absorbs himself completely in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes, describing what he experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations, and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in the waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, Kasten summarizes, “can cause a distortion of what we call reality.”
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
