75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their maternity
Discrimination in the workplace has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Feudality and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of job held.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get into a relationship earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
In contrast, women with stable jobs, mainly in the public sector, push back entry into life as a couple and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of beginning of common life, "explains the researcher of the CSIC Margarita Delgado.
Education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35- to 49-year-old group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
“Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those with elementary education get married and have their first child before finding stable employment, those with middle or higher education reverse this program and prioritize getting stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
