After rosy days since last spring, during which asset inflation has been the dominant rating in the markets, uncertainty is again emerging, which is not surprising since it is their natural state, in an environment where agents make decisions about a future that is inherently uncertain.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilize markets has been to monetize debt through the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by giving abundant liquidity at near-zero rates, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilize.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have been virtually finalized and, without calling into question their non-conformist liquidity policy, are starting to put a little bit of sand in the wheels, as the ECB has done, with their one-year auction next week.
As a result, investors doubt the global economy’s ability to sustain an economic recovery without heterodox measures, and we are seeing a reversal in the reduction of risk premiums.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads are increasing again, although they remain very far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
States have been forced to socialize private risk and public debt is again affected.
There is once again a flight to quality and the United States, Japan and Germany have been the havens chosen by investors, provoking an increase in the differences between eurozone countries and Germany.
Spain was barely affected by this episode of instability, but then Standard & Poor's threatened a further downward revision of the qualification of the Kingdom of Spain.
